# qGridX

[![Python 3.11+](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.11+-blue.svg)](https://www.python.org/downloads/)
[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](LICENSE)

**Hybrid quantum-classical optimization for power-grid storage planning.**

qGridX implements a four-stage *cut-guided amortized sampling* pipeline that
combines a PCE-restricted Generative Quantum Eigensolver (PCE-GQE) with
classical power-system physics to solve the battery/microgrid
siting-and-sizing problem under AC power-flow and contingency constraints.

## Quickstart

```bash
pip install -e ".[dev]"
qgridx run --config configs/ieee14_demo.yaml
```

## Architecture

The pipeline runs as a loop:

1. **Classical preprocessing** — Load power system, build scenarios, initialize Ising model
2. **Quantum master (PCE-GQE)** — GNN encoder reads Ising graph; Transformer decoder generates circuits; CUDA-Q executes them; 3-basis readout estimates correlations
3. **Projection ILP** — Snap raw bitstrings to feasible plans (budget, one-hot sizing)
4. **Classical subproblem** — DC-SCOPF with N-1 checks, emit cuts, update via DPO

> **Important:** This is a *cut-guided heuristic*, not Benders decomposition.
> See [docs/architecture.md](docs/architecture.md) for the three correctness
> rules enforced in code.

